---
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import BookLayout from '../../layouts/BookLayout.astro';
import { buildToc } from '../../lib/toc';
import SystemDesignDashboard from '../../components/SystemDesignDashboard.astro';

const toc = buildToc(await getCollection('book'));
---

<BookLayout title="System-design dashboard" toc={toc}>
  <h1>System-design dashboard</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    The synthesizing tool. Every other module isolates one effect; this one ties
    them together through the <strong>system link budget</strong> (Ch. 8, eq. 8.1)
    and the <strong>accuracy / rate / latency trilemma</strong> (Ch. 12), the way
    the capstone design walks them (Ch. 31).
  </p>
  <p>
    Turn the six design knobs — generator moment, sensor area-turns, excitation
    frequency, AFE noise, integration time, and geometry (PDOP) — and watch the
    field-referred noise σ<sub>B</sub>, the position accuracy across the working
    volume, and the resulting update rate and latency all move together. Push the
    accuracy up by lengthening the integration time and the rate falls and the
    latency rises: the trilemma is not a slogan but a budget.
  </p>
  <SystemDesignDashboard />
  <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-slate-500">
    Defaults reproduce the Ch. 31 worked design (≈1 nT σ<sub>B</sub>, sub-mm
    mid-volume, ~8.7 ms latency). The σ<sub>pos</sub> curve uses the same CRLB law
    the Python <code>crlb_vs_range</code> simulation computes.
  </p>
</BookLayout>
